quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The else Statement[/h1]

An [b]if[/b] statement can be followed by an optional [b]else [/b]statement, which executes when the condition is [b]false[/b]. 
[b]Syntax:[/b] [code format="cpp"][b]if[/b] (condition) {
  //statements
}
[b]else [/b]{
 //statements
}[/code]
The compiler will test the condition: 
- If it evaluates to [b]true[/b], then the code inside the [b]if [/b]statement will be executed. 
- If it evaluates to [b]false[/b], then the code inside the [b]else [/b]statement will be executed.
[note]When only [b]one [/b]statement is used inside the if/else, then the curly braces can be omitted.[/note]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the missing parts of the following code:
[!raw!]
int x = 22;
{0} (x > 33) {
 cout << "x is greater than 33" << endl;
} 
{1} {
 cout << "x is not greater than 33" << endl;
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The else Statement [/h1]

[b]For example:[/b] [code format="cpp" codeId="195"]int mark = 90;

if (mark < 50) {
  cout << "You failed." << endl;
}
[b]else[/b] {
  cout << "You passed." << endl;
}

// Outputs "You passed."[/code]

[h1]The else Statement[/h1]

In all previous examples only one statement was used inside the if/else statement, but you may include as many statements as you want.

[b]For example: [/b] [code format="cpp" codeId="196"]int mark = 90;

if (mark < 50) {
  cout << "You failed." << endl;
  cout << "Sorry" << endl;
}
else {
  cout << "Congratulations!" << endl;
  cout << "You passed." << endl;
  cout << "You are awesome!" << endl;
}

/* Outputs
Congratulations!
You passed.
You are awesome!
*/[/code]

quizzes.question:
