if (x > 22) {
 {0} (x > 31) {
 {1} << "it works!" << endl;
 }
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Nested if Statements[/h1]

You can also include, or [b]nest[/b], if statements within another if statement.
[b]For example: [/b] [code format="cpp" codeId="197"]int mark = 100;

if (mark >= 50) {
  cout << "You passed." << endl;
 [b] if (mark == 100) {
    cout <<"Perfect!" << endl;
  }[/b]
}
else {
  cout << "You failed." << endl;
}

/*Outputs
You passed.
Perfect!
*/[/code]

[h1]Nested if else Statements[/h1]

C++ provides the option of nesting an unlimited number of if/else statements.
[b]For example:[/b] [code format="cpp" codeId="198"]int age = 18;
if (age > 14) {
  if(age >= 18) {
    cout << "Adult";
  }
  else {
    cout << "Teenager";
  }
}
else {
  if (age > 0) {
    cout << "Child";
  }
  else {
    cout << "Something's wrong";
  }
}[/code]
[note]Remember that all [b]else [/b]statements must have corresponding [b]if[/b] statements.[/note]

